SIMPLE: adjuration
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Adjuration
<hw>Ad`ju*ra"tion</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>adjuratio</ets>, fr. <ets>adjurare</ets>: cf. F.
<ets>adjuration</ets>. See <er>Adjure</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The
act of adjuring; a solemn charging on oath, or under the penalty of a
curse; an earnest appeal.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What an accusation could not effect, an <qex>adjuration</qex>
shall.</q> <rj><qau>Bp. Hall.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The form of oath or appeal.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Persons who . . . made use of prayer and
<qex>adjurations</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Adjuratory</ent>⟦br⟧
